emphasis.docTitle:
Open-holed trapdoor spiders of the genus
Teyl
(Mygalomorphae: Nemesiidae : Anamini) from Western Australia’s Pilbara bioregion: a new species and expanded phylogenetic assessment

subSection.paragraph:
JOEL A. HUEY 1,2,3,5 , MICHAEL G. RIX 4,1 , JEREMY D. WILSON 4 , MIA J. HILLYER 1 & MARK S. HARVEY 1,2
1

subSection.paragraph:
The open-holed trapdoor spiders of the genus
Teyl Main, 1975
from the Pilbara bioregion of Western Australia are investigated. A single endemic species from the southern Pilbara,
T. heuretes
sp. nov.
, is newly described, representing the northern-most occurrence of the genus in Australia . Legacy molecular data for Australian Nemesiidae , along with newly generated sequences for all described species of
Teyl
known from Western Australia , are analysed using Maximum Likelihood methods, providing molecular data for
T. heuretes
and an expanded phylogenetic assessment of the genus.
Key words: biogeography, Crassitarsae, new species, taxonomy

The open-holed trapdoor spiders of the genus
Teyl Main, 1975
are a poorly documented yet widely distributed group of Anamini Simon, 1889 endemic to Australia , with a range that extends from the Indian Ocean coastline of Western Australia east to at least western Victoria (
Harvey et al. 2018
). Like the co-occurring taxa
Idiosoma Ausserer, 1871
(family
Idiopidae Simon, 1889
) and
Proshermacha Simon, 1908
(
Nemesiidae Simon, 1889
), the genus
Teyl
reaches its highest diversity in the south-western land division of Western Australia , where they are a major component of the mygalomorph spider fauna. While a number of species are clearly dependent on southern-temperate mesic habitats in the far south of Western Australia (e.g. see Main 1985: 753–758 ), most occur in semi-arid or arid inland regions ( Fig. 1 ). Only six species have so far been described, including three from south-western Australia (see Main 1975 , 1983 , 1985 ) and three from western Victoria ( Main 2004 ). However, numerous undescribed species are present in Australian collections (MSH, MGR, unpubl. data), some of which were identified by
Castalanelli et al. (2014)
using barcoding molecular data, and including one (
Teyl
sp. ‘BYM1953/2683’) formally listed as Critically Endangered under the Western Australian Wildlife Conservation Act 1950 (see Western Australian Government Gazette 2018 ).

The Pilbara bioregion of north-western Australia ( Fig. 2 ) is a geologically heterogeneous and biologically diverse landscape in Western Australia’s northern arid zone, which has been the subject of numerous dedicated studies over the last decade exploring the biogeographic and biological significance of the region (e.g. Humphreys 2008 ;
Durrant et al. 2010
;
Harvey et al. 2011
;
Pepper et al. 2013
;
Castalanelli et al. 2014
;
Huey et al. 2019
). The Pilbara is now well recognised for its role in maintaining arid zone biodiversity during climatic instability since the late Miocene, and for providing a suite of terrestrial and subterranean refugia ( Humphreys 2008 ;
Pepper et al. 2013
;
Huey et al. 2019
). It is also an important overlap zone between tropical arid elements of the biota, and more temperate southern lineages (
Huey et al. 2019
). Indeed, the Pilbara bioregion represents the northern extent of several otherwise more southern or temperate lineages of mygalomorph spiders. For Idiopidae , the Pilbara is the northernmost extent of
Gaius Rainbow, 1914
(see
Rix et al . 2018b
, fig. 11),
Bungulla Rix, Main, Raven & Harvey, 2017
(see
Rix et al. 2018a
, fig. 11),
Euoplos Rainbow, 1914
(see
Rix et al. 2019
, fig. 3) and to a large extent
Idiosoma
. Among Nemesiidae , the Pilbara is the northernmost extent of
Teyl
( Fig. 1 ),
Hesperonatalius Castalanelli, Huey, Hillyer & Harvey, 2017
(see
Castalanelli et al. 2017
, fig. 2) and to a large extent,
Kwonkan Main, 1983
. The northern distribution of
Teyl
is especially interesting in that it mirrors that of the co-occurring idiopid genus
Gaius
, extending sparsely through the Murchison bioregion and in a band through the eastern Gascoyne and southern Pilbara ( Figs 1 , 2 ; cf.
Rix et al. 2018b
, fig. 11).

This paper is the first in a planned series of systematic and revisionary treatments of the genera
Teyl
and
Namea
Raven, 1984
in Australia (i.e., the ‘
Teyl
Group’ sensu
Harvey et al . 2018
). We here document the
Teyl
specimens currently collected from Western Australia’s Pilbara bioregion, and describe the single known species at the northern extent of the genus’ distributional range. We further provide newly generated nucleotide sequence data for all described species of
Teyl
from Western Australia , and present an expanded phylogenetic assessment of the genus.

Molecular and laboratory methods. Nucleotide sequences were newly generated for three specimens of
Teyl
from the Pilbara bioregion, along with seven specimens of
Teyl
representing previously described species or species morphologically similar to named species ( Tables 1 , 2 ). Sequence data for all three species of
Teyl
currently described from Western Australia (i.e.
T. damsonoides ( Main, 1983 )
,
T. luculentus Main, 1975
and
T. vancouveri ( Main, 1985 ))
were included (
T. damsonoides
) or newly sequenced (
T. luculentus
,
T. vancouveri
) for this study (with specimens sourced from at or near type localities in each instance), along with sequence data from four specimens from eastern South Australia , morphologically similar to the Victorian species
T. harveyi Main 2004
or
T. yeni Main 2004
. This combination of new Pilbara material and described species from type localities provided the molecular taxonomic framework required to apply an integrative species concept ( sensu de Queiroz 2007 ), and to complement the morphological taxonomy. Laboratory methods for DNA extraction, polymerase chain reaction (PCR), nucleotide Sanger sequencing and downstream sequence editing were otherwise as per
Harvey et al. (2018)
, with the same seven loci targeted: cytochrome c oxidase subunit I ( COI ; mitochondrial); 12S ribosomal RNA (12S; mitochondrial); 16S ribosomal RNA (16S; mitochondrial); 18S ribosomal RNA (18S; nuclear); 28S ribosomal RNA (28S; nuclear); histone H3 ( H3 ; nuclear); and elongation factor-1γ ( EF-1γ ).

Phylogenetic analyses. A concatenated matrix consisting of 38 representative specimens from
Harvey et al. (2018)
was combined with the 10 specimens of
Teyl
newly sequenced for this study ( Tables 1 , 2 ), for a final molecular dataset of 48 specimens and seven loci. To avoid an unnecessarily dense sampling of non-
Teyl Anamini
genera, a representative subset of at most five specimens from each genus were included in the final dataset, with
Stanwellia nebulosa (Rainbow & Pulleine, 1918)
set as the ultimate outgroup. Alignments were carried out using the MAFFT plug-in in Geneious ( Katoh and Standley 2013 ). Due to the phylogenetic breadth of the dataset, ribosomal gene alignments had many regions that were difficult to align. Therefore, the program G Blocks ( Castresana 2000 ; Talavera and Castresana 2007 ) was used to remove phylogenetically uninformative sites. The web tool was chosen for this task (http://molevol.cmima.csic.es/castresana/Gblocks_server.html), and the settings allowed for gaps and larger blocks. The resulting alignments were: 12S (318 bp); 16S (405 bp); 18S (1,761 bp), 28S (753 bp); COI (658 bp); H3 (328 bp) and EF-1ɣ (882 bp). Trees were built for each alignment separately using the RAxML plug-in (version 7.2.8) ( Stamatakis 2006 ) in Geneious using default settings, with 1,000 bootstrap replicates. A concatenated

This concatenated dataset was partitioned using Partition Finder v1.1 ( Lanfear et al. 2012 , 2014 ), which identified three partitions: 12S, 16S, COI codon 1, and H3 codon 3 (partition1); 18S, 28S, COI codon 2, EF-1ɣ , H3 codons 1 and 2 (partition 2); and COI codon 3 (partition 3). These partitions were analysed with the GTR+G substitution model, using the RAxML plug-in in Geneious using default settings. The robustness of nodes was estimated using 1,000 bootstrap replicates, and the final tree was visualised and edited in FigTree (http://tree.bio.ed.ac.uk/software/figtree/).

subSection.paragraph:
Maximum Likelihood analysis of the concatenated dataset recovered an overall topology ( Fig. 3 ) congruent with that of
Harvey et al. (2018
, fig. 3). The
Chenistonia
Group,
Teyl
Group,
Kwonkan
Group and
Aname
Group of
Harvey et al. (2018)
were all monophyletic, and nested genera within each clade were recovered in the same relative phylogenetic positions, with high support ( Fig. 3 ). The
Chenistonia
Group was found to be sister to the
Teyl
Group, both of which were sister to the
Aname
Group plus
Kwonkan
Group.

subSection.paragraph:
Within the genus
Teyl
, specimens that were collected from the Pilbara bioregion formed a genetically homogeneous lineage distinct (and phylogenetically distant) from all other described and undescribed species of
Teyl
included in the analysis ( Fig. 3 ), with a minimum pairwise genetic COI divergence of 16.7% between Pilbara specimens and ‘MYG053’ (represented in this analysis by WAM T96326 ). This Pilbara lineage is here newly described as
T. heuretes
sp. nov.
( Fig. 3 ). Currently described species were similarly recovered in disparate positions throughout the phylogeny, with eastern taxa ( T. nr
yeni
and T. nr.
harveyi
) not each other’s closest relatives. As noted by
Harvey et al. (2018)
, the genus
Teyl
is clearly a phylogenetically diverse assemblage of taxa with a complex biogeographic history, and a much larger molecular taxon sample is required to better understand the taxonomy and evolutionary history of the group.

subSubSection.paragraph:
Diagnosis. Most species of
Teyl
and
Namea
can be distinguished from all other Anamini by the presence of a reflexed embolus arising on the lateral or proximal side of the pedipalpal bulb ( Figs 14–16 ), combined with the absence of a megaspur on the male leg I tibia ( Figs 11–13 ). However, a number of species of both
Teyl
(e.g.,
T. damsonoides
) and
Namea
(e.g.,
N. callemonda Raven, 1984
,
N. dahmsi Raven, 1984
) have a presumably autapomorphic morphology whereby the embolus is not reflexed, but rather positioned distally on the bulb; these species can be distinguished from similar Anamini by the absence of a leg I megaspur on males, or by the absence of incrassate tarsi on the leg I of males. Similarly, a number of species of
Namea
(e.g.
N. calcaria Raven, 1984
,
N. dicalcaria Raven 1984
) have macrosetae on the male leg I tibia which are produced into a megaspur-like structure; these species can be distinguished from all other Anamini, except species of
Teyloides Main, 1985
, by the presence of a reflexed embolus; and from
Teyloides
by the absence of coiled spermathecae in females.

subSubSection.paragraph:
The diagnostic separation of
Teyl
and
Namea
is currently problematic, due largely to the absence of a phylogenetic hypothesis for
Namea
, and the presence of a number of confounding diagnostic characters at the generic level (an issue discussed in detail by Raven 1984 ). At present,
Teyl
includes all of those species which occur in western and southern Australia , outside of the subtropical and tropical mesic zone of eastern Queensland and north-eastern New South Wales . Whether
Namea
, as currently circumscribed ( sensu Raven 1984 ), represents one or more genera, and how it differs morphologically from
Teyl
s.s. , is currently the subject of ongoing research.

Distribution. Species of
Teyl
occur throughout the semi-arid and arid zones of southern Australia , from Western Australia ( Fig. 1 ) east to southern South Australia and western Victoria . The genus reaches its highest diversity in south-western Western Australia , although a relatively few species can be found as far north as the Murchison, Gascoyne and Pilbara bioregions in the western-central arid zone ( Figs 1 , 2 ).

Included species. The genus
Teyl
includes seven described species, one of which is newly described in this study. Numerous undescribed species are also known from throughout western and southern Australia .

Diagnosis. Males of
Teyl heuretes
can be distinguished from
T. damsonoides
by the presence of a reflexed embolus ( Figs 14–16 ; cf. Main 1983 , fig. 51); from
T. harveyi
,
T. vancouveri
, and
T. walkeri
by the length of the embolus, which is much longer relative to the width of the bulb ( Figs 14–16 ; cf. Main 1985 , fig. 24; Main 2004 , figs 8, 19); and from
T. luculentus
and
T. yeni
by the absence of conspicuous macrosetae on metatarsus I ( Fig. 11 ; cf. Main 1975 , fig. 2C; Main 2004 , fig. 35). Females are unknown.

Etymology. The specific epithet is derived from the Greek
heuretes
(finder, inventor, discoverer; see Brown 1956 ), in reference to the species with the most northern distribution of the genus ( Fig. 1 ), and for Keiran John (Jack) Devery, the maternal grandfather of the first author, who spent his life improving himself and learning new skills to discover the world around him.
